In Code Now
(x,y) = True,False
if x:
  print("x")

if x and y:
  print("x and y")

if x or y:
  print("x or y")

if x and not y:
  print("x and not y")

if not(x and y):
  print("not x and y")

if x is the simplest: if True then print "x". There is no logic, we just do it or we don‚Äôt depending on whether x is True.
if x and y is the ‚Äòpark and ice cream question‚Äô: there‚Äôs no ice cream without going to the park. So both things have to be True for this to work out happily and print("x and y").
if x or y is the ‚Äòcereal or toast for breakfast‚Äô question: my daughter is having breakfast either way, so if she answers ‚ÄòYes‚Äô (True) to either then it doesn‚Äôt matter that the other one is False, she‚Äôs still had breakfast, or we‚Äôre still printing ‚Äúx or y‚Äù. And note, if she was really hungry and said yes to both then that would also be breakfast. So if they are both True that‚Äôs also fine.
if x and not y: is the negation of one term. So ‚Äòif you behave and don‚Äôt touch that again then you will get a treat‚Äô is what we‚Äôre looking for here. But you can also negate the entire thing: not(x and y) is also valid logic. So this turns a False on if x and y into a True.

